## Building an E-commerce Product Filter Grid in Angular

**Mental model:** Keep products immutable; filters (categories `Set`, max price, sort) are fields; the shown grid is a getter chaining filter → sort. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them), no `FormsModule`.

### Step 1 — Filter fields
```typescript
cats = new Set<string>();
maxPrice = 500;
sort = 'none';
```

### Step 2 — Derive shown (getter)
```typescript
get shown(): Product[] {
  let r = this.products.filter((p) => (this.cats.size === 0 || this.cats.has(p.category)) && p.price <= this.maxPrice);
  if (this.sort === 'asc') { r = [...r].sort((a, b) => a.price - b.price); }
  if (this.sort === 'desc') { r = [...r].sort((a, b) => b.price - a.price); }
  return r;
}
```

### Step 3 — Toggle category
```typescript
toggleCat(c: string): void { if (this.cats.has(c)) { this.cats.delete(c); } else { this.cats.add(c); } }
```

### Step 4 — Grid + count
```html
<p>{{ shown.length }} products</p>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| No category | Means "all". |
| Empty result | Empty state. |
| Sort copy | `[...r].sort`. |

**Interview tip:** A getter chaining the facets keeps the grid consistent automatically; an empty category `Set` meaning "all" sidesteps a special select-all control.

